Princess Noriko was born on 22 July 1988 at Aiiku Hospital in [[:en:Minami-Azabu|Minami-Azabu]], [[:en:Tokyo|Tokyo]]. After her birth, her father, Prince Takamado, chose her name. She went to Gakushuin Kindergarten. After that she attended the prestigious [[:en:Gakushūin|Gakushuin]] School for her primary, junior high, and high school education.

In April 2007, Princess Noriko enrolled in the [[:en:Gakushuin University|Gakushuin University]], Faculty of Letters, Department of Psychology, and expressed her intent to pursue studies in the field of [[:en:clinical psychology|clinical psychology]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Personal History of Her Imperial Highness Princess Takamado and her family |url=http://www.kunaicho.go.jp/e-about/history/history08.html |publisher=[[Imperial Household Agency]] |date=|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>

In July 2008, she came of age and attended official ceremonies in Japan with the other members of the Imperial Family. She attended official functions at the palace and accompanied her mother to some other official events, as well as attending some on her own. On 20 March 2011, she graduated from Gakushuin University with the [[:en:Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree in [[:en:Psychology|Psychology]].

===Marriage===
On 27 May 2014, Princess Noriko announced her engagement to {{nihongo|Kunimaro Senge|千家国麿|Senge Kunimaro|extra= born {{Birth date|1973|9|2|df=y}}}}, a [[kannushi]] for the [[Izumo-taisha]] shrine.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wedding Bells to Ring for Japanese Princess|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2014/05/27/wedding-bells-to-ring-for-japanese-princess/|newspaper=Wall Street Journal Japan}}</ref> The two married on 5 October at the shrine.<ref name=wedding1>{{cite web|title=Princess Noriko marries son of Izumo Taisha priest, relinquishes royal status|date=5 October 2014 |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/10/05/national/princess-noriko-marries-son-of-izumo-taisha-priest-relinquishes-royal-status/#.VDFoc1e5_y0|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marriage of Her Imperial Highness Princess Noriko of Takamado - Wedding Ceremony at the Izumo Oyasahiro Shrine in Shimane Prefecture|url=http://www.kunaicho.go.jp/e-about/activity/gokekkon-h26/e-kekkonsiki-ph.html|work=The Imperial Household Agency|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>

Senge Kunimaro is the eldest son of Senge Takamasa, the head priest of the Izumo Grand Shrine. The [[:en:Senge family|Senge family]] have been hereditary administrators of the shrine for generations.<ref name=wedding1/> Though legally commoners today, the heads of the family held the title of [[:en:Baron|Baron]] in the Imperial Japanese peerage (''[[kazoku]]'') before its abolition in 1947. Senge Kunimaro is a second cousin (twice removed) of the present Emperor and a distant cousin twice over of Princess Noriko. He and Noriko are third cousins once removed by their shared descent from Prince [[:en:Kujō Michitaka|Kujō Michitaka]], who was the father of the Empress Teimei, Princess Noriko's great-grandmother and Senge Kunimaro's great-great-aunt.<ref name=Senge_descent>{{cite web|url=https://reichsarchiv.jp/%e5%ae%b6%e7%b3%bb%e3%83%aa%e3%82%b9%e3%83%88/%e5%8d%83%e5%ae%b6%e5%ae%b6%ef%bc%88%e5%87%ba%e9%9b%b2%e5%9b%bd%e9%80%a0%e5%ae%b6%ef%bc%89#kunimaro973|title=千家家（Izumo Province 造家） (Senge genealogy)|website=Reichsarchiv|access-date=17 May 2017|language=ja}}</ref> The couple are also fifth cousins through their shared descent from Marquis [[:en:Nakayama Tadayasu|Nakayama Tadayasu]], the maternal grandfather of the [[:en:Emperor Meiji|Emperor Meiji]].<ref name=Nakayama_descent>{{cite web|url=https://reichsarchiv.jp/%e5%ae%b6%e7%b3%bb%e3%83%aa%e3%82%b9%e3%83%88/%e4%b8%ad%e5%b1%b1%e5%ae%b6%ef%bc%88%e7%be%bd%e6%9e%97%e5%ae%b6%ef%bc%89#suketikaq|script-title=ja:中山家（羽林家）|website=Reichsarchiv|access-date=17 May 2017|language=ja}}</ref> By birth, Kunimaro is also related to other members of the imperial family. He is a sixth cousin once removed of his grandmother-in-law, [[:en:Princess Mikasa|Princess Mikasa]], a third cousin twice removed of [[:en:Princess Hitachi|Princess Hitachi]] and a cousin of the late Princesses [[:en:Kikuko, Princess Takamatsu|Takamatsu]] and [[:en:Setsuko, Princess Chichibu|Chichibu]] (a second cousin thrice removed and a fourth cousin thrice removed, respectively).<ref name=Senge_descent/><ref name=Nakayama_descent/>

After the wedding, Princess Noriko lost her imperial status. This change in her status is mandated by the [[:en:Imperial Household Act|Imperial Household Act of 1947]] that requires females of the Imperial Family to relinquish their title from birth, official membership in the Imperial Family, and [[:en:allowance (money)|allowance]] from the state upon marriage to a commoner. At 26 years of age, she became the seventh female member born into the [[:en:Imperial House of Japan|Japanese Imperial Family]] to marry a commoner since the passage of the [[:en:Imperial Household Law|Imperial Household Law]] in 1947, and the first member of the family to lose her royal status since the marriage of [[:en:Sayako Kuroda|Sayako, Princess Nori]], [[:en:Akihito|Emperor Akihito's]] daughter, in 2005. The government decided to bestow a one-time ¥106.75 million allowance on the couple.<ref name=wedding1/>

